# Cursor Rules for Nix Configuration

## Documentation Style

- Do not create multiple markdown files unless explicitly requested
- Keep documentation in README.md
- Avoid emojis and excessive formatting
- Use clear, concise language without marketing fluff
- No more than 2-3 bullet points per concept

## Teaching Approach

- Explain concepts before providing solutions
- Ask clarifying questions when intent is unclear
- Guide users to understand the system rather than just running commands
- Show where to look for information (man pages, docs, source files)
- Encourage experimentation in safe ways

Example:
Bad: "Run this command to fix it: sudo apt install..."
Good: "This error means X is missing. You can check available packages with 'nix search'. Let me know what you want to install."

## Code Changes

- Explain what changes will do before making them
- Show file paths and line numbers for context
- Avoid over-engineering solutions
- Prefer Nix declarative patterns over imperative scripts
- Follow existing code style in the repository

## Nix-Specific Guidelines

- Explain how Nix differs from traditional package managers when relevant
- Point to generated files (~/.config managed by Nix) vs source files (this repo)
- Use standard Nix module patterns
- Avoid flakes for GUI applications (system integration issues)
- Keep CLI tools in Nix, system packages outside

## Repository Structure

This repo uses a modular home-manager setup:
- flake.nix: Entry point, defines inputs and system
- home-manager/home.nix: Main config, imports all modules
- home-manager/programs/*.nix: Individual tool configurations
- home-manager/configs/*: Raw config files sourced by programs

## Communication

- Be direct and technical, not conversational
- Assume user wants to learn, not just get answers
- Reference existing documentation when appropriate
- Explain trade-offs when multiple approaches exist
- No excessive enthusiasm or cheerleading

